ce:section.ce:para:
Earlier, we reported that prophylactic application of CQDs significantly induced antiviral immune responses in CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected plants (Farooq et al., 2024). To further investigate the CQDs-modulated transcriptional immunity in CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected N. benthamiana, we sought to utilize nanoscale monodispersed CQDs (Supplementary Fig. 1) and analyze the DEGs associated with early (5 dpi) and late (20 dpi) stage antiviral immune responses. Monitoring transcriptional activity revealed that CQDs application altered the expression of 20 antiviral immunity-related genes in the presence of CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β) at 5 dpi (Fig. 2A; Table 1
                        ). The majority of these genes were upregulated and included important factors such as the WRKY transcription factor, Ca2+/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase (CaMK), serine/threonine protein kinase (STPK), K+-channel ERG and related proteins, including the PAS/PAC sensor domain (Fig. 2B; Table 1). Notably, significantly high expression (log2-fold change = 1.23638; p value = 0.01058) was observed for Niben261Chr02g1075009, which is a CaMK (Fig. 2B; Table 1). This protein contains two conserved STPKc-CaMK and PTZ00184 domains, with the former containing multiple active ATP and polypeptide substrate binding sites (Fig. 2C). Furthermore, we found that the number of antiviral immunity/defense-related genes among the CQDs-treated plants increased to 32 among the CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected plants at a later stage (20 dpi) (Fig. 2D; Table 2
                        ). Similar to the expression pattern observed at 5 dpi, most of these genes, including calmodulin, RPM-1-interacting protein, STPK, mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK), WRKY-type transfactor, calponin and NADH/NADPH oxidase, were upregulated (Fig. 2D; Table 2). Interestingly, of the 32 genes, only the expression of the K+-channel ERG was downregulated, whereas the highest expression was observed for a calmodulin-like (CML) protein (Niben261Chr09g1291016) (Fig. 2E; Table 2). This CML protein contains several typical EF-hand motifs, along with conserved FRQ1 and Efh_CREC superfamily domains (Fig. 2F). Comprehensive results regarding the activation of antiviral/immunity-related genes in CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected plants without CQDs treatment at 5 and 20 dpi are given in Supplementary Tables 3 and 4, respectively. Overall, these results suggest that the CQDs significantly induced antiviral immunity-related transcriptional responses in the CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected plants at the early (5 dpi) and late (20 dpi) stages, with later involving higher number of defense-related transcription factors.

Alternative splicing confers transcriptomic and proteomic diversity in many organisms, including plants, and governs several important biological processes, such as plant disease resistance and immunity, among others (Godinho et al., 2024). Since our previous findings suggest that CQDs induce antiviral immunity through the modulation of AS events in N. benthamiana (Farooq et al., 2024), we sought to comprehensively map the frequency and patterns of CQDs-induced AS events in response to CLCuMuV infection. The results of the AS analysis revealed that CLCuMuV infection alone induced multiple AS patterns in N. benthamiana at 5 dpi, among which 3 prime AS events were the most frequently detected (50 %) (Fig. 3A). However, the CQDs application induced a differential pattern, resulting in 28.7 % detection of the “intron_retention” AS event. Importantly, with a slightly lower frequency (27.1 %), “mutually exclusive exons/(mutex_exons)” AS events were found in the CQDs-treated plants, which remained undetectable in the absence of CQDs (Fig. 3B). Furthermore, we mapped all genes associated with the most frequently detected “intron_retention” AS at 5 dpi. A detailed description of the genes associated with “intron_retention” AS events, the significance values, exon positions, DPSI scores, and PFAM categories is provided in Table 3
                        . Moreover, at 20 dpi, a total of 5 AS events were observed in the CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected plants in the absence of CQDs treatment. Among these events, “intron_retention” was the most frequently (35.7 %) detected AS event, followed by 3 prime AS events, with a 21.9 % frequency (Fig. 3C; Table 4
                        ). On the other hand, the application of the CQDs markedly altered the AS landscape of the virus-infected plants, where “exon_skipping” was the most frequently (33.9 %) detected AS event, followed by 3 prime AS events, with a 32.1 % frequency (Fig. 3D). Taken together, these results suggest that CQDs regulate the differential patterns and frequency of AS events in CLCuMuV (DNA-A + β)-infected plants and that these changes vary with the progression of viral infection.
